  "doc_id": "52394",
  "text": "+ memory B cells [CITATION_1] . CD27 is now an important marker for analysis of B-cell differentiation in diseases characterized by disturbances in B-cell development. In fact, distinct types of abnormal Of interest, previous reports had already mentioned a decrease in IgD + CD27 + memory B-cell subset in patients with SLE [CITATION_2] , primary SS [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] or SSc [CITATION_6] . Also, a reduction in circulating memory B cells was demonstrated in patients with X-linked Hyper-IgM syndrome [CITATION_7] , chronic granulomatous disease [CITATION_8] and HIV infection [CITATION_9] . Hence, lower levels of circulating memory B cells seem to be hallmark linked with chronic inflammation rather than an exclusive feature of autoimmune conditions. Furthermore, in a study performed by Hansen et al. [CITATION_10] , it was shown that the generation of the peripheral B-cell memory subset in SS patients seems to be particularly affected by abnormalities in post-recombination events. Our observations suggest that changes in the B-cell memory subset also occur in very early stages of RA and other polyarthritis. In VERA patients, despite the clinical response induced by corticosteroids and MTX, no effect of these treatments was reflected in changes of IgD + CD27 + memory B-cell levels.",
